1. Place breakpoints as shown above and F5
2. Once Breakpoint [1] is hit insert a new line at [3] (in between ```{``` and ```// [3]```)
3. F5, Breakpoint [2] is hit, step 5 times (until the current IP is out of the exception handler.

**Expected Behavior**:

Current IP (yellow span) is at ```Console.WriteLine(4);```

**Wrong Behavior**:

Any other span is highlighted (specifically ```Console.WriteLine(4);``` is skipped and  ```Console.WriteLine(5);``` is highlighted).

**Version Used**: 

15.6.0 P1.1

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Console app, place breakpoints as indicated, F5

```C#
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            try
            {
                G();
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                Console.WriteLine();
                Console.WriteLine(); // breakpoint #1 here
                Console.WriteLine();
            }
        }

        static void G()
        {               
            throw new Exception(); // breakpoint #2 here
        }
    }
```

When breakpoint 2 is hit add 5 empty lines in front of breakpoint 1 and continue via F5. Breakpoint 1 won't be hit. This is because the debugger is not able to map the breakpoints within exception region whose span changes. We need to disallow any changes to the exception region span that affect line numbers of sequence points within the span, not just semantically significant changes.

issue_comments.body:
@mattwar 
Don't confuse

`yield foreach recFN` with `yield x On iter`

`yield foreach recFN` is equivalent to

```
foreach(x in recFN) 
{
 yield x;
}
```

Which is still Quadratic.

This does something different. Let's use another example. Yielding the permutations of a list of items.

```
private iterator _Perm<T>( items : T[], len : int, res : T[] , iter : Iterator<T[]> ) : IE< T[] >
{
  if( items.Length = len )
  {
   Yield res On iter;
  } else
  {
    for(var i = 1 To items.Length)
    {
      _Perm<T>( items.Skip(1).ToArray(), len, res.Concate( items.Take(1) , iter );
      items = items.Rotate();
    }
  }
}


public Rotate<T>( this a : T[] ) : T[]
{
  return a.Skip(1).Concate( a.Take(1) ).ToArray();
}`
```

Let's create the public method the initiates the iterator and calls the method.

```
public Perm<T>( this items : T[] , size : int ) : IE< T[] >
{
  if( items == null ) return Empty<T[]>();
  if( items.Length = 0 ) return Empty<T[]>();
  if( size < 1 ) return Empty<T[]>();
  if( size > items.Length ) size = items.Length;
  return _Perm<T>( items , size, {} , Iterator.Create( _Perm<T> ) );
}
```

`Iterator.Create( _Perm<T> );` create the **single instance** of the iterator / yielder that is use through out the recursive calls.
Maybe an attribute`[Iterator(Recusive:= True)]` on the function, creates the "linearised" state-machine.

